# 2.7 -  10 Lesson Connections

Within the Big Idea of Data, the CSP Framework focuses heavily on how data and information facilitate the creation of knowledge.  In the second half of this unit, students will use the computer to manage and visualize data in order to organize it into useful structures that provide a thorough, accurate interpretation of that data into information. In this set of lessons, students will look at data that already exists, and consider how it may be interpreted.  In doing so, they will also reflect on what makes a good visualization and how flawed assumptions can influence data analysis.


## Lesson 7: Introduction to Data
<img src="https://images.code.org/f1b819301fd401c2014b8d35d7ea56b0-image-1475956442058.jpg" style="float:right; margin-left:30px; width:200px">

**Lesson Type:** Unplugged | External Tools | Individual and Group Discovery

<a href = "https://curriculum.code.org/csp/unit2/7/" target=_blank> Lesson Plan Link <i class="fa fa-external-link-square"></i></a>



This lesson introduces many of the lessons and themes that will run through the unit: identifying patterns and relationships, interpreting data/information, and making connections and inferences. Students are introduced to the Class Data Tracker, which is a Google form that they will complete each day to collect data that they will later interpret. They also begin thinking about the many ways data impacts their lives and how it can be used. While the primary goal of this lesson is to get ideas and processes in place for the rest of the unit, there are many places where students can start asking interesting questions about where and how data is collected, who is collecting it, and how they are using it.
