## Lesson 8: Finding Trends with Visualization
<img src="https://images.code.org/a14ca88318a8acc562133ed477ce68dc-image-1475956442059.png" style="float:right; margin-left:30px; width:200px">

**Lesson Type:** External Tools | Research | Presentation

<a href = "https://curriculum.code.org/csp/unit2/8/" target=_blank> Lesson Plan Link <i class="fa fa-external-link-square"></i></a>

Lesson 8 helps students get acquainted with talking and writing about data.  In particular, we want to make sure that they are able to draw a distinction between describing *what* the data shows and describing *why* the data look the way they do.  In other words, students should be able to describe connections and trends in data separately from drawing conclusions about the data. This will allow them to separate the ‘what’ from the ‘why’ when it comes to talking and writing about data. The next lesson looks deeper into assumptions that people make about data that can lead to unintentional consequences.
<br><br><br>
<hr />

## Lesson 9: Check your Assumptions

**Lesson Type:** External Tools | Research | Presentation

<a href = "https://curriculum.code.org/csp/unit2/9/" target=_blank> Lesson Plan Link <i class="fa fa-external-link-square"></i></a>

<img src="https://images.code.org/463a7b1536eef59fec32c9da73115811-image-1475956442060.png" style="float:right; margin-left:30px; width:200px">

In this lesson we look deeper into why we separate the ‘what’ from the ‘why’ when looking at data. The main purpose here is to raise awareness of the assumptions that we (all people) make when looking at data, and try to call those assumptions out. This is a useful mode of reflection that will serve students well when doing reflective writing on the performance tasks.
Analyzing and interpreting data will typically require some assumptions to be made about the accuracy of the data and the cause of the relationships observed within it. When decisions are made based on a data, they will often rest just as much on that set of assumptions about the data as the data itself. Identifying and validating (or disproving) assumptions is therefore an important part of data analysis. Furthermore, clear communication about how data was interpreted should also include an account of the assumptions made along the way.
